The code data(mtcars) loads the built-in dataset named mtcars into the R environment. This dataset contains information about various attributes of 32 different car models. Each row represents a car model, and each column represents a different attribute of the cars.

These statistics provide insights into the distribution and central tendency of each variable in the dataset. Additionally, the cor(mtcars) function computes the correlation matrix for the variables in the mtcars dataset, showing the pairwise correlations between variables. This matrix provides information about the strength and direction of linear relationships between variables. Lastly, the pairs(~mpg disp hp drat wt qsec vs am gear carb, data=mtcars) function generates a scatterplot matrix, which visualizes pairwise relationships between variables in the mtcars dataset. Each cell in the matrix displays a scatterplot of one variable against another, allowing for visual examination of potential relationships between variables.

# Scatterplot matrix
pairs(~mpg+disp+hp+drat+wt+qsec+vs+am+gear+carb, data=mtcars)

Interpreting the output:For the simple linear regression model, the coefficient of am is interpreted as the difference in mpg between automatic and manual transmissions.For the multiple linear regression model, the coefficients represent the effect of each predictor variable on mpg, holding other variables constant. The significance of each coefficient is indicated by the p-values. Lower p-values (< 0.05) suggest that the corresponding variable is significantly associated with mpg. The R-squared values indicate how well the models fit the data. Higher values suggest better fit.The F-statistic assesses the overall significance of the regression model. A low p-value (< 0.05) indicates that at least one predictor variable is significantly related to the response variable.

model_simple <- lm(mpg ~ am, data = mtcars)
model_multiple <- lm(mpg ~ am + disp + hp + drat + wt + qsec + vs + gear + carb, data = mtcars)

These lines of code extract and calculate the differences in miles per gallon (mpg) between two types of transmission systems (automatic and manual) based on the coefficients obtained from the linear regression models. In summary, these calculations provide insight into the impact of transmission type on fuel efficiency (mpg) as predicted by the simple and multiple linear regression models.

coefficients_simple <- coef(model_simple)
coefficients_multiple <- coef(model_multiple)

mpg_difference_simple <- coefficients_simple[2]
mpg_difference_multiple <- coefficients_multiple['am']

mpg_difference_simple
##       am 
## 7.244939
mpg_difference_multiple
##       am 
## 2.577428

Based on the analysis and plots performed: The simple linear regression model (model_simple) suggests that, on average, manual transmissions have approximately 7.24 mpg higher than automatic transmissions. However, when considering other variables in addition to transmission type, as in the multiple linear regression model (model_multiple), the difference in mpg between automatic and manual transmissions decreases to approximately 2.58 mpg. Both models indicate that manual transmissions tend to have higher mpg compared to automatic transmissions, but the exact difference varies depending on whether other variables are considered in the analysis. The difference in mpg between automatic and manual transmissions is estimated to be around 7.24 mpg according to the simple linear regression model, and approximately 2.58 mpg according to the multiple linear regression model. Overall, based on the analysis performed, manual transmissions appear to be more fuel-efficient in terms of mpg compared to automatic transmissions.

plot(model_simple)
